With the September 16 deadline looming it seems ever less likely that this deal will be sealed 'on time'. Rather the challenges that face TikTok in trying to change their data infrastructure to accommodate a sale to Microsoft are massive. It seems highly unlikely that an acquisition, which takes long enough between domestic companies, of a Chinese firm by a US firm in two similar but different industries could be rushed. While there may be mounting pressure, it does not seem plausible that this process can be rushed by another executive order.

On one hand, trump has said that he will not extend the deadline for tiktok. On the other hand, the probability of a deal deteriorates with each passing day. I'm adjusting my sep 16 - oct 31 down and before sep 16 up slightly, but overall I think these two events mostly cancel each other out.

Like My colleagues, we can simplify this problem into event spaces. The first is Event(A) = Microsoft does not announce deal before November 1. I view this option as the same as if Microsoft not announcing a deal at all. In a recent news, China has implemented new export restrictions that potentially can block or delay any deal for ByteDance to sell operations to the US. Further, the US elections is on November 2nd, and if President Trump does not win, the pressure for ByteDance to sell TikTok may dissipate. I also believe that if ByteDance sells TikTok before November 1st, it will come across as if sold only because Trump forced them too, a weak image for Chinese tech stocks that China would likely not want to display.
Two components, timing and acquirer:
Reducing odds of before Sept 16 by 10% due to possible China regulation that could stop the deal from happening.

The first goal is to determine the probability that Microsoft will be the one to announce the deal given a deal is announced. The two main players seem to be Microsoft and Oracle, although it seems other players may be interested. Regardless, Microsoft seems to be the frontrunner, so I’ll give it a 75% chance of getting the acquisition at all. There have been frequent delays due to regulation, but it seems Trump has given the company a deadline of November 12. Thus, I believe if the deal were to happen, it would need to happen before then. It is difficult to estimate the probability of the deal being announced, but at this point it seems like there is over a 90% chance given the number of interesting players having discussions.

Even though usually we would model scenarios starting with an outside view, TikTok is not a usual acquisition case, but is rather a unique one off event created by macro factors. Therefore, to come up with a distribution for the announcement date, we used a more situation dependent approach.

I broke down this question into two sub-questions: 1) Will Microsoft be the one who acquired Tik Tok, and 2) if 1) is true, when the announcement will be. Up until 9/3/2020, Trump has announced that Tik Tok now has an extra 45 days to complete the acquisition on or before 11/15/2020, China has put additional protective measures on Tik Tok's core algorithm, and Oracle/Softbank are joining the bidding war.

Because this is such an unpredictable question, I had to make some assumptions. The first was that Microsoft/Walmart and Oracle, the two most likely groups to acquire Tik Tok, are interchangeable. I assumed that since the first group has two major players, it has a 2/3 chance to receive the deal, conditional on a deal occurring.

From what it seems so far, sources are very conflicted regarding the possibility of a TikTok deal actually going through. On August 2, Microsoft made a statement saying that it would make a decision on TikTok in a matter of weeks "and in any event completing these discussions no later than September 15, 2020." (https://blogs.microsoft.com/blog/2020/08/02/microsoft-to-continue-discussions-on-potential-tiktok-purchase-in-the-united-states/)

Aug 6th trump signed an executive order that would ban transactions with Tiktok withint 45 days. Hence the original September 20th deadline. However, on Aug 14th, trump signed another executive order that gives Bytedance, Chinese parent company of Tiktok, 90 days to negotiation a sale. That extends the deadline to November 14 (with possible 30 day extension at Trump's discretion) .With that said, Trump also said during a past interview/conference that the original September 20th deadline still holds. He might meant it or he might just be confused. WH has sent mixed signals on Tiktok news. On the other hand, last Friday (August 28th) China revised a list of technologies that are banned or restricted for export for the first time in 12 years. The changes would apply to TikTok, and it can take up to 30 days to obtain preliminary approval to export technology.Some rumor is that China wants to stall the deal until post US elections. A lot of mixed news around Tiktok and the main snag right now is indeed whether AI technology would be included in the sale. In terms of successful bidders, if there is indeed a deal, I am estimating 80% for MSFT/WMT joint offer and 15% for ORCL and 5% for others (GOOG/TWTR/Investment Management firms). I had MSFT at 80% because from a business perspective, MSFT is better. Also, ORCL's 20bn deal seems low (granted it was with existing ByteDance investors) and the US administration will not like the kickback clause where they kick back 50% of profits back to ByteDance for 2 years. Summarizing all the above, my estimation for answers is 50% for it to come by September 16th given the advanced deal talk so far, 10% for September 16 and October 31st (with most probability mass concentrated between September 16th and September 20th) and 40% for it to fall either after November 1st or another bidder gets TikTok.

In the third bucket you need to consider: 1\ The acquisition will not happen. First publicly confirmed on August 2nd, the proposed TikTok acquisition comes in response to months of escalating concerns about Chinese ownership of an app used by millions of Americans. Microsoft, Oracle, and Triller have all put in bids to purchase TikTok’s operations in the US, Canada, Australia, and New Zealand (roughly 30 percent of worldwide users) to allay the concerns. . On Friday, China quietly added personalized content recommendation algorithms to its list of export-controlled items, throwing the deal into chaos. The new export controls mean that any recommendation algorithm — like the one that powers TikTok’s For You page — will need government approval before it can be sold to a foreign company. [1] According to Harvard Business Review, between 70 and 90 percent of mergers and acquisitions fail. [2] So given that China changed its export rules for the first time in 12 years and that data is the highly valuable for Chinese government I will put a 70% here.

First, it is not certain that a deal will occur, and even if it does, MSFT is not the only group vying to purchase TikTok. Assume MSFT's group has 60% chance of winning (over Oracle) given that a deal occurs, which is a conservative estimate that takes into account MSFT's and WMT's combined strength (increase prob) and also Bill Gates' negative comments towards the deal (decrease prob). Now, we consider the probability that a deal actually occurs before 1Nov. Trump's stated deadline is 12Nov, which is strongly pushing probability towards a deal occurring. However, we also consider that China's government has stated it must review the deal, and their antagonistic stance towards Trump. Thus, we can estimate an 65% chance that a deal occurs before 1Nov, regardless of buyer. The above process gives a 61% chance that MSFT is not involved in a deal before 1Nov

This is hilarious, and quite instructive. Excerpt below for those of you too tight to pay 1.99 a month for Bloomberg. (Disclaimer: no affiliation with Bloomberg whatsoever. I actually prefer Reuters)

Oracle has entered the competition now, adding yet another competitor to the fray. However, a recent Fox Business article had multiple sources claiming that a piece of paper will be signed by the cut-off date of September 15th (which signifies as announcement) while the official deal will not be executed for several more months. September 16th is only a few days before Trump's ban of the app takes effect, meaning if a deal is going to be struck between Microsoft and ByteDance, it will almost definitely be announced before then. Microsoft has recently announced their interest in acquiring the app and, after initially threatening to ban the app altogether, Trump has announced his official support for the acquisition. This is important for two reasons. (1) It shows Microsoft is serious about buying it and believes it is in a strong enough position to openly admit that (no backdoor deals or playing it close to the chest). (2) It suggests that the President intends to ban the app if the deal were not to go through, meaning ByteDance would lose a huge amount of money if they don't sell. As such, Microsoft will likely get a deal on the sale and ByteDance would be able to avoid huge losses, a rare win-win for such a large acquisition. Once the app is banned within the US, however, Microsoft's incentive to buy becomes almost zero (and potentially negative given legal and administrative expenses) and ByteDance will have already absorbed the loss. Therefore, the situational economics suggest that the deal should at least be announced sooner rather than later.
